 boilerplate is to understand that reversing an N-bit vector $X$ is equivalent to taking $X$ and reordering its elements. In SystemVerilog, we can use a loop inside a `generate` block or rely on procedural assignment if we were to break it down, but since we aim for minimal code and combinational purity, the continuous assignment is key.\n\nGiven the constraints and the nature of bit reversal, we must explicitly map $out[i] = in[99-i]$. This is best done via an `always @(*)` block or by using a generated assignment, but for simplicity and directness adhering to the combinational nature, we will use an `always @(*)` block to implement the assignment relationship explicitly, which is functionally equivalent to the continuous assignment but easier to manage for arbitrary bit-widths if needed.\n\n*Final Choice:* Using an `always @(*)` block to assign $out[i] = in[99-i]$ for all $i$ from 0 to 99 ensures correctness and adheres to the combinational logic requirement, while avoiding the extremely long concatenation list.",
